===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr}} {{term|charade|lang=fr}}, {{term|charrade||[[prattle]], [[idle]] [[conversation]]; a [[kind]] of [[riddle]]|lang=fr}}, probably from {{etyl|oc}} {{term|charrada||[[conversation]]; [[chatter]]|lang=oc}}, from {{term|charrar||to [[chat]]; to [[chatter]]|lang=oc}} + {{term|-ada|lang=oc}}<ref>"charade, ''n.''" in the ''Oxford English Dictionary'', 3rd ed., 2014.</ref>
[[Category:English terms borrowed from French]]

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|shəräd"|shərād"}}, {{IPA|/ʃəˈɹɑːd/|/ʃəˈɹeɪd/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|shərād"}}, {{IPA|/ʃɚˈɹeɪd/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪd|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A specific kind of [[riddle]] in which a word or phrase to find is split in several parts that can each be guessed from a [[verbal]] [[clue]].
# {{qualifier|in plural}} A [[party game]] in which players [[mime]] a word, phrase, or name that the other players must try to guess.
# Something apparently real but based on [[pretence]]/[[pretense]].
#: ''She said she loved me but it was only a '''charade'''.''

